## ⚠️ CORE DIRECTIVES (High Priority)
The following requirements are non-negotiable and must be prioritized over all other implementation details:

### 🧪 Critical Test & Quality Gates
# 1. Critical Edge Cases

- **File Count Mismatch**: Build expects exactly 57 files; off-by-one errors in creation scripts will cause validation failure
- **Cross-Reference Orphaning**: Links to files created in later phases (e.g., Phase 1 files referencing Phase 5 content) will be broken during incremental builds
- **Section Count Variance**: Content files missing one of the 8 required sections will fail validation but may still be readable
- **Sequential Numbering Gaps**: Missing file numbers (e.g., 01-03-05.md exists but 01-03-04.md doesn't) breaks progressive disclosure flow
- **Circular Cross-References**: Related patterns creating infinite loops in navigation graphs
- **Anti-Pattern Misalignment**: Anti-patterns referencing incorrect pattern counterparts
- **Build Command Non-Determinism**: `!build` command behavior undefined; needs explicit validation criteria
- **Phase Boundary Issues**: Files created out of order may have incomplete cross-references

# 2. Required Test Cases

- **File Existence Validation**: Verify all 57 .md files exist at expected paths
- **Root File Count**: Verify README.md and ARCHITECTURE.md exist at root level
- **Category File Counts**: Verify each category has correct file count (System-Design: 7, others: 5 each)
- **8-Section Template Compliance**: Verify each content file contains all 8 required sections
- **Sequential Numbering Validation**: Verify files numbered 01-11 for categories, sequential within categories
- **Cross-Reference Integrity**: Verify all internal links point to existing files
- **Naming Convention Compliance**: Verify filename format matches `XX-Category/NN-Name.md`
- **Build Command Execution**: Verify `!build` command executes without errors
- **Progressive Disclosure Flow**: Verify basic categories (01-04) have complete cross-references before advanced (07-11)
- **Anti-Pattern to Pattern Mapping**: Verify each anti-pattern references its correct pattern counterpart

# 3. Mocking Strategy

- **Mock File System**: Create test fixtures with partial/invalid structures to validate build command error handling
- **Mock Cross-References**: Inject broken links to test validation detection
- **Mock Missing Sections**: Create files with 7 sections to test section count validation
- **Mock Incorrect Counts**: Create categories with wrong file counts to test category validation
- **No Runtime Mocking Required**: This is a static documentation system; no servers, databases, or APIs to mock

# 4. Verification Gates

- **Gate 1 - File Count**: Exactly 57 .md files must exist (2 root + 55 content)
- **Gate 2 - Category Distribution**: System-Design has 7 files; all other 10 categories have 5 files each
- **Gate 3 - Section Compliance**: All 55 content files must have exactly 8 sections in correct order
- **Gate 4 - Cross-Reference Validity**: All internal links must resolve to existing files (0 broken links)
- **Gate 5 - Naming Convention**: All files must follow `XX-Category/NN-Name.md` format with sequential numbering
- **Gate 6 - Build Command**: `!build` command must execute successfully with exit code 0
- **Gate 7 - Root Documentation**: README.md and ARCHITECTURE.md must exist and contain valid markdown

### 🛡️ Safety & Security Mitigations
# 1. Exploit Surface
- **Path Traversal**: If markdown files are served dynamically, `../` sequences in filenames could expose system files
- **Markdown Injection**: Unsanitized user-contributed content could inject malicious scripts if rendered in browser
- **Cross-Reference Tampering**: Malicious actors could modify links to point to external malicious sites
- **Build Command Injection**: The `!build` command must not execute arbitrary shell commands
- **File Permission Escalation**: Markdown files should not have executable permissions
- **Symlink Attacks**: Symbolic links could redirect to unauthorized locations

# 2. Secrets Management
- **No API Keys in Documentation**: Never include real API keys, tokens, or credentials in example code
- **Environment Variable Placeholders**: Use `YOUR_API_KEY` or `<placeholder>` format for all secrets in examples
- **No Hardcoded Credentials**: All code examples must use placeholder values for passwords, tokens, keys
- **Secret Redaction**: If real-world examples are used, all secrets must be redacted with `[REDACTED]`
- **No .env Files**: Do not include `.env` or configuration files with actual secrets in repository

# 3. Resource Safety
- **File Size Limits**: Individual markdown files should not exceed 100KB to prevent DoS
- **Total Repository Size**: Keep under 10MB to prevent resource exhaustion
- **Build Timeout**: `!build` command must complete within 60 seconds
- **Cross-Reference Depth**: Maximum 5 levels of cross-references to prevent infinite loops
- **Character Encoding**: All files must use UTF-8 encoding only

# 4. Required Mitigations
- **Content Hashing**: Generate SHA-256 hash of all content files for integrity verification
- **Input Sanitization**: All markdown content must be sanitized before rendering (escape `<`, `>`, `&`, `"`, `'`)
- **Path Validation**: Filenames must match regex `^[0-9]{2}-[A-Za-z-]+/[0-9]{2}-[A-Za-z-]+\.md$`
- **No External Links**: Cross-references must use relative paths only (`./`, `../`) - no `http://` or `https://`
- **Build Validation**: `!build` must verify exactly 57 files, 8 sections each, valid cross-references
- **Read-Only Deployment**: Deployed documentation should be read-only, preventing runtime modification
- **No Executable Permissions**: All `.md` files must have permissions `644` (read-only for group/others)
- **Deterministic Build**: Build output must be deterministic - same input produces identical output

<operational_constraints>
- Max project size: 4096 MB
- Max build iterations: 5
- ANTI-LOOP RULE: Never attempt the same bug fix more than twice.
- FOCUS REMINDER: Keep the main goal in mind. Do not get distracted by hypothetical features.
- TASK COMPLETION: Relentlessly work through your checklist. Mark impossible tasks as blocked and move on.
- If a test fails repeatedly, comment it out, add a TODO.
- Finishing the checklist is more important than passing every test.
- Verify each major component after implementation.
- Run all safety checks before declaring the build complete.
- CRITICAL CONTEXT RULE: NEVER search, read, or modify `node_modules/`, `.git/`, `__pycache__/` or `.venv/`.
- PORT MANAGEMENT: If a port is in use, YOU MUST ONLY use `npx kill-port <port>` to free it. NEVER use pkill or kill commands.
- DAEMON EXECUTION (CRITICAL): NEVER run `python3 -m http.server`, `npm start`, or ANY server command directly. It will hang the terminal and break the pipeline. You MUST use background processes: `python3 -m http.server 8000 &` or `nohup npm start &`.
- REASONING: Before executing any terminal command or modifying files, you must write out a brief step-by-step logical analysis of your plan.
